{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600428"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:03:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:03:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15615"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15615"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.16,0.05,0.63,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8306"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15615"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiac examination reveals a soft ejection systolic murmur at the left upper sternal border. An echocardiogram is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the anatomical significance of the infundibulum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Connection between left atrium and left ventricle","Junction between left ventricle and aorta","Area of right atrium receiving venous return","Muscular tunnel connecting right ventricle to pulmonary artery","Region between tricuspid valve and right ventricular apex"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe infundibulum, also known as the conus arteriosus, is a key anatomical structure in cardiac anatomy. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe muscular tunnel connecting the right ventricle to pulmonary artery\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the infundibulum. This smooth-walled, funnel-shaped portion of the right ventricle forms the right ventricular outflow tract and is crucial for normal pulmonary blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe connection between left atrium and left ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E is actually the mitral valve apparatus, which includes the valve leaflets, chordae tendineae, and papillary muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe region between tricuspid valve and right ventricular apex\u003C/strong\u003E is the inflow portion of the right ventricle, which has a trabeculated appearance unlike the smooth infundibulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe area of right atrium receiving venous return\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the sinus venosus portion of the right atrium, where the superior and inferior vena cavae enter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe junction between left ventricle and aorta\u003C/strong\u003E is the left ventricular outflow tract, which contains the aortic valve but does not have an infundibular structure like the right side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomy of the infundibulum is particularly important in congenital heart disease, where abnormalities such as infundibular stenosis can occur. It is also relevant when interpreting cardiac imaging and during cardiac surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The infundibulum is the funnel-shaped portion of the right ventricle that leads to the pulmonary artery.","The infundibulum is also known as the conus arteriosus or right ventricular outflow tract.","The infundibulum is a key anatomical landmark in congenital heart disease assessment."],"references":["Netter, F. H. 1. (2019). Atlas of human anatomy. Seventh edition. Philadelphia, PA, Elsevier."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15615"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T11:43:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T11:44:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8306"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71113"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi